a]]\n*{{flagicon|ECU|1900}} [[Iv\u00e1n Kaviedes]]\n*{{flagicon|ECU|1900}} [[Christian Lara (footballer)|Christian Lara]]\n*{{flagicon|ECU|1900}} [[Franklin Salas]]\n*{{flagicon|ECU|1900}} [[Carlos Tenorio]]\n{{col-3}}\n*{{flagicon|PAR|1990}} [[Julio C\u00e9sar C\u00e1ceres]]\n*{{flagicon|PAR|1990}} [[Diego Gavil\u00e1n]]\n*{{flagicon|PAR|1990}} [[Gustavo Mor\u00ednigo]]\n*{{flagicon|PAR|1990}} [[Jorge Mart\u00edn N\u00fa\u00f1ez]]\n*{{flagicon|PAR|1990}} [[Nelson Haedo Valdez]]\n*{{flagicon|PER}} [[Santiago Acasiete]]\n*{{flagicon|PER}} [[Claudio Pizarro]]\n*{{flagicon|PER}} [[Gustavo Vassallo]]\n*{{flagicon|URU}} [[Nelson Abeijon]]\n*{{flagicon|URU}} [[Paolo Montero]]\n*{{flagicon|URU}} [[\u00c1lvaro Recoba]]\n*{{flagicon|URU}} [[Mario Regueiro]]\n*{{flagicon|URU}} [[Cristian Rodr\u00edguez]]\n*{{flagicon|URU}} [[Dar\u00edo Rodr\u00edguez]]\n*{{flagicon|URU}} [[Adri\u00e1n Romero]]\n*{{flagicon|VEN|1954}} [[H\u00e9ctor Gonz\u00e1lez (Venezuelan footballer)|H\u00e9ctor Gonz\u00e1lez]]\n*{{flagicon|VEN|1954}} [[Jos\u00e9 Manuel Rey]]\n*{{flagicon|VEN|1954}} [[Leonel Vielma]]\n{{col-end}}\n\n;1 own goal\n{{col-begin-small}}\n{{col-3}}\n*{{flagicon|BOL}} [[Herm\u00e1n Sol\u00edz]] (playing against [[Ecuador national football team|Ecuador]])\n*{{flagicon|BRA}} [[Gilberto Silva]] (playing against [[Uruguay national football team|Uruguay]])\n{{col-3}}\n*{{flagicon|PER}} [[Luis Guadalupe]] (playing against [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]])\n*{{flagicon|VEN|1954}} [[Alejandro Cichero]] (playing against [[Bolivia national football team|Bolivia]])\n{{col-3}}\n*{{flagicon|VEN|1954}} [[Jos\u00e9 Manuel Rey]] (playing against [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]])\n{{col-end}}\n\n== Broadcasting rights ==\n\n{{Empty section|date=April 2020}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[2010 FIFA World Cup qualification (CONMEBOL)]]\n*[[2002 FIFA World Cup qualification (CONMEBOL)]]\n\n{{2006 FIFA World Cup qualifiers}}\n\n[[Category:2006 FIFA World Cup qualification|CONMEBOL]]\n[[Category:FIFA World Cup qualification (CONMEBOL)]]\n[[Category:2003 in South American football|World]]\n[[Category:2004 in South American football|World]]\n[[Category:2005 in South American football|World]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox international football competition\n| image = \n| size = \n| tourney_name   = 2006 FIFA World Cup qualification (CONMEBOL)\n| year           = \n| alt            = \n| caption        = \n| host countries = \n| dates          = {{nowrap|6 September 2003 \u2013 12 October 2005}}\n| num_teams      = 10\n| confederations = 1\n| matches        = 90\n| goals          = 235\n| attendance     = \n| top_scorer     = {{flagicon|BRA}} [[Ronaldo (Brazilian footballer)|Ronaldo]] {{nowrap|(10 goals)}}\n| prevseason     = [[2002 FIFA World Cup qualification (CONMEBOL)|2002]]\n| nextseason     = [[2010 FIFA World Cup qualification (CONMEBOL)|2010]]\n}}\n{{Qualification for championships (CONMEBOL)}}\nListed below are the dates and results for the '''[[2006 FIFA World Cup qualification]]''' rounds for '''[[CONMEBOL|South America]]'''.  10 teams took part, all in a single group.  The rules were very simple: the teams would play against each other in a home-and-away basis, with the four teams with most points qualifying to the [[2006 FIFA World Cup]]. The fifth ranked team would have to play-off against the best team from [[2006 FIFA World Cup qualification (OFC)|Oceania]], with the winner of this play-off also qualifying. For the first time, [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]], the defending champion, was required to go through qualification and was not automatically qualified for the tournament.\n\n==Tiebreakers==\n{{Football World Cup 2006 Qualifying tiebreakers}}\n\n==Standings==\n{|\n|-\n|\n{{2006 FIFA World Cup qualification - CONMEBOL\n| expanded    = yes\n| fixtures    = yes\n}}\n|\n|}\n*'''Brazil''', '''Argentina''', '''Ecuador''' and '''Paraguay''' qualified for the [[2006 FIFA World Cup]].\n*'''Uruguay''' advanced to the [[2006 FIFA World Cup qualification (CONMEBOL-OFC play-off)|CONMEBOL/OFC play-off]].\n\n==Results==\n\n===Round 1===\n----\n{{football box\n|id = Ecuador v Venezuela\n|date = 6 September 2003\n|time = 16:00 [[UTC-5]]\n|team1 = {{fb-rt|ECU|1900}}\n|score = 2\u20130\n|report = [https://web.archive.org/web/20071023235438/https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/germany2006/preliminaries/preliminary=7302/matches/match=33811/report.html Report]\n|team2 = {{fb|VEN|1930}}\n|goals1 = [[Giovanny Espinoza|Espinoza]] {{goal|5}}<br/>[[Carlos Tenorio|C. Tenorio]] {{goal|72}}\n|goals2 =\n|stadium = [[Estadio Ol\u00edmpico Atahualpa]], [[Quito]]\n|attendance = 14,997\n|referee = [[Rub\u00e9n Selman]] ([[Federaci\u00f3n de F\u00fatbol de Chile|Chile]]) }}\n----\n{{football box\n|id = Argentine v Chile\n|date = 6 September 2003\n|time = 16:00 [[UTC\u22123]]\n|team1 = {{fb-rt|ARG}}\n|score = 2\u20132\n|report = [https://web.archive.org/web/20071023235450/https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/germany2006/preliminaries/preliminary=7302/matches/match=33813/report.html Report]\n|team2 = {{fb|CHI}}\n|goals1 = [[Kily Gonz\u00e1lez|C. Gonzalez]] {{goal|32}}<br/>[[Pablo Aimar|Aimar]] {{goal|35}}\n|goals2 = {{goal|60}} [[Milovan Mirosevic|Mirosevi\u0107]] <br />{{goal|77}} [[Reinaldo Navia|Navia]] \n|stadium = [[Estadio Monumental Antonio Vespucio Liberti]], [[Buenos Aires]]\n|attendance = 35,372\n|referee = [[Ubaldo Aquino]] ([[Asociaci\u00f3n Paraguaya de F\u00fatbol|Paraguay]]) }}\n----\n{{football box\n|id = Peru v Ecuador\n|date = 6 September 2003\n|time = 20:15 [[UTC\u22125]]\n|team1 = {{fb-rt|PER}}\n|score = 4\u20131\n|report = [https://web.archive.org/web/20071023235433/https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/germany2006/preliminaries/preliminary=7302/matches/match=33809/report.html Report]\n|team2 = {{fb|PAR|1990}}\n|goals1 = [[Nolberto Solano|Solano]] {{goal|34}}<br />[[Andr\u00e9s Mendoza (Peruvian footballer)|Mendoza]] {{goal|42}}<br />[[Jorge Soto (footballer)|Soto]] {{goal|83}}<br />[[Jefferson Farf\